0022-audio-eq-output.patch            # services/audio/output_controller.{cc,h} + chrome/browser/chrome_content_browser_client.cc -> browser-wide output EQ: a preamp + RBJ-biquad cascade (ZwireAudioEq) applied in OutputController::OnMoreData() to EVERY output stream the audio service pulls before the OS device, so ALL tab audio (media element, MSE/YouTube, Web Audio, WebRTC) is equalized. The renderer AudioRendererMixer was the wrong layer (streaming tabs bypass it, inRMS=0); the audio service is the universal chokepoint (YouTube inRMS!=0). Config passed as the --zwire-audio-eq switch: the sandboxed/re-signed macOS audio utility does NOT inherit the ZWIRE_AUDIO_EQ env, so ChromeContentBrowserClient::AppendExtraCommandLineSwitches reads the browser-process env and forwards it as a switch (switches survive the sandbox; env does not). bin/zwire exports the env from $STATE/audio-eq. Same RBJ math as the HUD dashboard eq.js. NOTE: config is now a process-global, live-swappable snapshot (see 0024) — ZwireAudioEq reads it every block and rebuilds its per-stream cascade for its own sample rate when the generation changes; the launch switch/env only seeds it. The engine is ALWAYS-ON by default: empty/no-config => unity (audio still routed through it), only "off"/"0" bypasses. Chain (zdsp-core port + standard DSP blocks): preamp -> EQ cascade -> gain(0..4) -> drive(tanh soft-clip) per channel, then stereo-linked feed-forward compressor, then stereo feedback delay/echo, then reduced-Freeverb reverb (4 combs + 2 all-passes/ch), then M/S stereo width, then equal-power pan (sqrt2-normalized so pan=0 is transparent) / mono fold, then a brickwall limiter (instant-attack peak, dead-last so nothing re-clips). Spec adds 2-field directives after the bands: "gain,<lin>;pan,<-1..1>;mono,<0|1>;drive,<0..1>;thresh,<dB>;ratio,<n>;width,<0..2>;delay,<ms>;feedback,<0..0.95>;delaymix,<0..1>;reverb,<0..1>;room,<0..1>;damp,<0..1>;ceiling,<-30..0 dB>". Each new block is unity/bypass by default and per-stream (own buffers), so the engine stays bit-identical passthrough until engaged. (VERIFIED compiled + runtime @150.0.7871.46 via logs: engine engages by default at unity with NO file [gen=1 gain=1 pan=0 drive=0], and gain=0.5/pan=-0.7/drive=0.6 all parse + apply live on file change)
0024-audio-live-config.patch          # services/audio/public/mojom/audio_service.mojom + services/audio/service.{cc,h} + content/browser/audio/audio_service.cc -> LIVE, always-on config for the 0022 output EQ, with nothing open and no relaunch. The audio sandbox can't read $STATE/audio-eq (VERIFIED: ReadFileToString ok=0 in the audio process), so the unsandboxed browser process is the reader: content/browser/audio/audio_service.cc polls the file off-thread every 700ms and, on change, pushes the spec via the new mojom AudioService::SetZwireEqConfig; Service forwards to audio::SetZwireEqConfig() which atomically swaps the process-global ZwireEqConfig (see 0022's output_controller.cc). Cache-guarded (no push when unchanged → no cascade-rebuild churn) + re-pushes on audio-service (re)launch. Poll interval 25ms; combined with the page writing the spec directly over the persistent native port (fs_write, NOT a per-knob sendNativeMessage→exec /bin/sh spawn) + a ~30ms leading/trailing throttle, knob→engine latency dropped from ~160ms to ~40-50ms. ALSO carries the fork-patch-0025 output METERS back-channel (folded into these same files): the audio service computes a compact meter frame (Goertzel spectrum bars + peak/RMS L/R + phase correlation + decimated stereo scope) of the REAL post-DSP output in ZwireMeterWrite/ZwireMeterSnapshotJson (output_controller.cc), the browser pumps it via mojom AudioService::GetZwireMeters and atomically writes $STATE/meters ~30fps, and the HUD Audio page reads it over the native-host persistent port (fs_read) to render the charts — NO tabCapture (which mutes the source + drops audio on release), so the charts are a true live view of the engine and closing the page never touches audio. The meter pump runs on a dedicated ThreadPool SequencedTaskRunner (NOT BrowserThread::UI) via a new bindable ZwireMeters sub-interface (mirrors BindSystemInfo: one-time UI hop to bind the pipe, then Pull()+reply on the pool sequence): the old UI-thread RepeatingTimer+GetZwireMeters starved to <1fps during a scroll/trackpad GESTURE (the compositor-gesture scheduler saturates the UI thread), which froze the meters file and made the charts "freeze until you release the mouse". Off the UI thread the file stays live (~30fps) through any gesture. (VERIFIED compiled + runtime via CDP: edited $STATE/audio-eq live → engine reshaped within ~160ms; tone playing → meter frame maxbar 0.99/pL 1.0 in $STATE/meters; and under a synthesized touch gesture the meters file went from 0.7/s [UI-thread pump] to 10+/s [pool pump] and the page feed held 27.5/s vs 2/s — user-confirmed the scroll-freeze is gone.)
0023-audio-tab-capture.patch          # chrome/common/extensions/api/_api_features.json + chrome/browser/extensions/api/tab_capture/tab_capture_api.cc -> let the HUD Audio dashboard pull a playing tab's real output into its analyzer/EQ chain. (1) api_features: make the tabCapture API available to hud-internal (hash DCE846DF…) WITHOUT the manifest tabCapture permission (2nd allowlisted feature variant, mirrors 0016). (2) tab_capture_api GetAllowlistedExtensionID(): default the allowlisted id to hud-internal (omcgnnjf…) when --allowlisted-extension-id is unset, so getMediaStreamId({targetTabId}) bypasses the activeTab grant with no picker/prompt. audio.js gets the id via the SW (background.js zwire-audio-capture) and consumes it with getUserMedia(chromeMediaSource:'tab'); tabCapture taps the same audio-service Snooper as loopback = the tab's true final output. Grant change is scoped to this one id only. (VERIFIED compiled @150.0.7871.46 + runtime via CDP: chrome.tabCapture available with NO manifest permission, getMediaStreamId returns an id with no activeTab/picker/prompt, and getUserMedia(chromeMediaSource:tab) delivered a playing tab's real PCM to an analyser — captured peak 0.3256 == the 0.30-gain test tone)
